Roctracer: Fix contention for high QPS cases and add upper limit for buffer size (#893)

Summary:
Pull Request resolved: https://github.com/pytorch/kineto/pull/893

This diff fixes the crashing issue when number of samples is high.
- Adds a mutex for activity_callback and and api_callback when adding rows into buffer
- Adds a thread_local mutex and unordered_map in api_callback due to jemalloc SIGABRT, seems like contention on timestamp.
- Use a shared insert_row_to_buffer() function to lock when storing the row to buffer.

FIXME: We don't currently delete the rows in the buffer, since we need to keep them around until the chrome trace is created. We should fixed this by transferring ownership to CuptiActivityProfiler via Activity Buffer similar to Cupti Activity.

Test Plan: CI and internal workloads.

Refactor Roctracer activities to match Cupti Activities to re-use existing logger logic (#892)

Summary:
Pull Request resolved: https://github.com/pytorch/kineto/pull/892

This diff refactors the Roctracer activities to match Cupti activities, and performs the following changes:
- Switch roctracer activities from GenericTraceActivity to derived structs of ITraceActivity
- Re-use existing logic for mapping linked activities, populating resourceInfo, checking timestamp ordering and out of range.
- Use templates to handle a variety of roctracer rows, most of templates belong to runtime events, which have varying metadata.
- Clean up RoctracerActivityApi and consolidate all roctracer rows into a single buffer with row struct encapsulation.
- Finally clean up unused functions, variables, duplicate definitions, etc.

FIXME: need to propagate runtime metadata into GPU event metadata.

Test Plan: CI and internal workloads.

Fix CUPTI timestamp on Windows (#868)

Summary:
I am working on enabling CUPTI on pytorch on Windows https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/pull/111568 but I had some flaky tests in the CI caused by https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/main/test/test_foreach.py#L65. After some debugging, I realized that sometimes the tensor_apply_kernel will be `TraceActivity outside of profiling window:`. The issue is caused by the fact that on Windows timestamp from CUPTI is on Windows the monotonic time so we try to sync the system clock with the steady clock.

But after CUDA 11.6 it was added [cuptiActivityRegisterTimestampCallback ](https://forums.developer.nvidia.com/t/cuda-profiler-tools-interface-cupti-for-cuda-toolkit-11-6-is-now-available/200030) for which we register a callback that returns the system time which seems to be the better option.

This branch is used in https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/pull/111568 which runs the unit tests which pass.
Let me know if there are some additional tests I should do.

Pull Request resolved: https://github.com/pytorch/kineto/pull/868

Reviewed By: xuzhao9

Fix for cudaEventSynchronize() in CUDA sync activity tracer (#862)

Summary:
Pull Request resolved: https://github.com/pytorch/kineto/pull/862

With cuda event sync we were missing one type of "Event Sync" operation due to some existing filtering logic we added earlier.
There are four types of synchronization CUDA supports
1. Context/Device Sync - CPU waits for GPU  (cudaDeviceSynchronize)
2. Stream Sync- CPU waits for GPU stream   (cudaStreamSynchronize)
3. Event Sync- CPU waits for GPU CUDA event  (cudaEventSynchronize)
4. Stream Wait for Event - Inter GPU stream sync  (cudaStreamWaitEvent)

{F1429132758}
{F1429133328}
We were not logging (3) above correctly. Stream Wait events were ending up being too noisy so we added filtering for them. But this inadvertently removed Cuda Event Sync events.
The changes include
1.  Adding a new function `isWaitEventSync` to determine whether an activity is a wait event synchronization specifically.
2. Modifying the `CuptiActivityProfiler::handleCudaSyncActivity()` method to not filter out Event Syncs
3. Updated test case.

Reviewed By: chaekit

fbshipit-source-id: 6f6efc15946a02575e785cace96282a8c77b5d90

Enable profiler initialization for CPU only use cases

Summary:
This PR enables profiler initialization for CPU only use cases. The main goal is to enable on-demand profiling with a daemon when using CPU only mode of PyTorch.
* When CUDA is available the profiler is initialized on first CUDA stream creation (or lazily when profiler is run).
* Since the CUDA stream creation callback does not exist on CPU only PyTorch the profiler is never initied on its own.
* Thus the job does not register with Dynolog when we set "KINETO_USE_DAEMON" env variable to set.
* This PR tries to fix this.

Part of the resolution for https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/112389 and https://github.com/facebookincubator/dynolog/issues/208

Reviewed By: chaekit
